<HL>
   Procter &amp; Gamble Co.
   Weighs Expanding
   Plant Near Cincinnati
</HL>
<DATE>
08/01/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   PG
</CO>
<IN>
HOUSEHOLD AND PERSONAL-CARE PRODUCTS (HHP)
</IN>
<LP>
   CINCINNATI -- Procter &amp; Gamble Co. is considering a $200
million expansion of its century-old Ivorydale plant near
this city.
   P&amp;G officials say the soap and detergent plant is one of
several midwestern U.S. plants that could be expanded as part
of its restructuring.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Local officials expect the expansion following the
Cincinnati consumer products company's request for a property
tax abatement on $200 million in plant improvements.
   P&amp;G yesterday won a 75% property tax abatement for new
buildings and machinery at the site. The abatement could save
P&amp;G up to $15 million in taxes over 10 years, said David
Main, executive director of Hamilton County Development Co.,
the county's economic development agency.
   A spokeswoman for P&amp;G said the abatement makes the
Ivorydale site competitive with other locations, but
expansion plans aren't official because "there are several
projects under consideration."
   Other P&amp;G sites that could be expanded include laundry and
cleaning products plants in Alexandria, La., and Augusta,
Ga., or a peanut-butter plant in Lexington, Ky. P&amp;G could
choose to build a plant at another site, according to a
company spokeswoman.
   It's unclear whether the Ivorydale expansion will include
new products or simply shift production from other plants
that P&amp;G plans to close.
   For instance, P&amp;G has announced plans to close its Port
Ivory plant in Staten Island, N.Y. That plant employs 425
people and makes soaps, detergents and cleaners.
</TEXT>
