<IN>
BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)
MORTGAGES, MORTGAGE BANKERS, MORTGAGE-BACKED SECURITIES (MOR)
</IN>
<LP>
   The following were among yesterday's offerings and
pricings in U.S. and non-U.S. capital markets, with terms and
syndicate manager, as compiled by Dow Jones Capital Markets
Report.
                                                                                                       

                      CORPORATES
                                                                                                       

</LP>
<TEXT>
   Sears, Roebuck &amp; Co. -- $300 million of 9 1/4% notes due
Aug. 1, 1997, priced at 99.885 to yield 9.272%. The size of
the issue was increased from $250 million. The non-callable
notes were priced at a spread of 0.98 percentage point above
the Treasury's seven-year note. Rated single-A-1 by Moody's
Investors Service Inc. and single-A-plus by Standard &amp; Poor's
Corp., the issue will be sold through underwriters led by
Goldman, Sachs &amp; Co.
   American Express Credit Corp. -- $200 million of 8 5/8%
notes due Aug. 1, 1994, priced at 99.65 to yield 8.73%. The
non-callable notes were priced at 0.625 percentage point
above the Treasury's four-year note. Rated double-A-2 by
Moody's and double-A by S&amp;P, the issue will be sold through
underwriters led by Lehman Brothers.
   Kimberly-Clark Corp. -- $100 million of 9% notes, due Aug.
1, 2000, was priced at 99.64 to yield 9.055%. The
non-callable notes were priced at a spread of 0.70 percentage
point above the Treasury's 10-year note. Rated double-A-2 by
Moody's and double-A by S&amp;P, the issue will be sold through
underwriters led by Goldman Sachs.
                                                                                                       

                      MUNICIPALS
                                                                                                       

   Huntsville, Ala., Solid Waste Disposal Authority -- $87
million of solid waste disposal and resource recovery revenue
bonds, Series 1990, have been priced by a Merrill Lynch
Capital Markets group. The bonds were priced to yield from
6.40% in 1994 to 7.40% in 2014. They are rated triple-A by
Moody's and S&amp;P and are insured.
   Oklahoma Industries Authority -- $76.4 million of hospital
revenue bonds, Series 1990 A, have been priced by a Goldman
Sachs group. The total amount of the issue has been raised
slightly from $76 million. The bonds, for the Baptist Medical
Center of Oklahoma, yield from 6.20% in 1993 to 7.20% in
2014. Bonds due in 2000 and later are callable Aug. 15, 2000,
at 102, declining to par on Aug. 15, 2002.
                                                                                                       

                       MORTGAGE
                                                                                                       

   Federal Home Loan Mortgage Corp. -- $400 million of
subordinated callable debentures has been priced at par to
yield 9.15%. The securities are due Aug. 8, 2000, and are
callable on or after Aug. 8, 1995. The securities must be
purchased in minimum amounts of $5,000 with additional
increments of $5,000. The securities were priced at a spread
of about 0.80 percentage point over 10-year Treasury notes.
   Federal Home Loan Mortgage Corp. -- $300 million of real
estate mortgage investment conduit securities is being
offered in 15 classes by UBS Securities, a unit of Union Bank
of Switzerland. The offering, Series FHLMC 190, is backed by
Freddie Mac 9 1/2% securities with a weighted average coupon
rate of 10.12% and weighted average remaining term to
maturity of 29.23 years. Pricing was at market levels.
   Federal National Mortgage Association -- $300 million of
Remic securities is being offered in 14 classes by Merrill
Lynch Capital Markets. The offering, priced Friday through
Series 1990-101, is backed by Fannie Mae 9% securities.
   Federal National Mortgage Association -- $300 million of
Remic securities is being offered in 16 classes by J.P.
Morgan Securities. The offering, Series 1990-102, is backed
by Fannie Mae 9% securities with a weighted average coupon
rate of 9.70% and weighted average remaining term to maturity
of 29.67 years. Full details on yields and prices weren't
immediatly available.
                                                                                                       

                       EUROBONDS
                                                                                                       

   West German government (sovereign) -- three billion marks
($1.89 billion) of 8 1/2% bonds due Aug. 21, 2000, at 100 1/2
to yield 8.42%, via Deutsche Bundesbank. Entire amount placed
via the fixed federal bond consortium.
   Unilever NV -- One billion French francs ($188 million) of
9 7/8% bonds due Sept. 4, 1997, priced at 101.40 to yield
9.97% less fees via BNP Capital Markets Ltd. Fees 1 7/8.
   Deutsche Genossenschaftsbank (West Germany) -- 250 million
marks of bonds with equity-purchase warrants attached for
Berliner Handels-und Frankfurter Bank stock with a 3 1/2%
coupon due Dec. 21, 1995, and priced at par, via Deutsche
Genossenschaftsbank. Each 1,000 mark bond carries two
warrants, exercisable from Oct. 2, 1990, to Dec. 1, 1995, to
buy two shares of BHF stock for 510 marks apiece. Each 10,000
mark bond carries 20 warrants to buy 20 shares of stock under
the same terms.
   Abbey National Treasury Services PLC (United Kingdom
parent) -- 150 million European currency units of 10 1/8%
bonds due Aug. 21, 1995, priced at 101 1/8 to yield 10 1/8%
less fees via Swiss Bank Corp. Guaranteed by Abbey National
PLC. Fees 1 7/8.
   Credit Foncier de France (France) -- 150 million European
currency units of 9 3/8% bonds due Dec. 27, 1999, priced at
98.97 via Societe Generale. Fungible with the original 150
million ECU issue launched in November 1989. Guaranteed by
the Republic of France.
   European Telecommunications Satellite Organization
(agency) -- 100 million European currency units of 10% bonds
due Aug. 28, 1992, priced at 101 1/8 via Dresdner Bank.
