<HL>
   Group Led by Morse
   Sells F.A.O. Schwarz
   To a Dutch Concern
   ---
   Recovering From a Slump,
   Toy Retailer Has Chance
   To Expand Into Europe
   ----
   By Udayan Gupta
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
08/01/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B2
</SO>
<CO>
   N.KBB
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
SPECIALTY RETAILERS (OTS)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- F.A.O. Schwarz has a new owner again -- the
sixth since the founding family sold the famous toy-store
chain in 1963.
   Koninklijke Bijenkorf Beheer N.V., Amsterdam, purchased
the 17-store chain from an investor group led by the
Philadelphia investment banker Peter Morse. That group had
acquired F.A.O. Schwarz in 1985 and engineered its current
recovery.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Terms of the latest sale weren't disclosed, but an
industry executive estimated the price at about $40 million,
nearly four times what the Morse group paid in 1985. F.A.O.
Schwarz said its sales will exceed $50 million this year.
   The transaction won't change the way F.A.O. Schwarz
operates, said Peter Harris, its chief executive officer. The
current management team will continue to operate
independently, he said, but "KBB's financial strength will
give F.A.O. new capital to grow and fuel its expansion into
Europe."
   The purchase of F.A.O. Schwarz gives KBB, a Dutch retail
conglomerate with sales of $2.2 billion in 1989, its first
major acquisition in the U.S. The high-end retailing business
is a niche that has proved extremely attractive to foreign
buyers. Investcorp International Inc., a partnership of
Arabian investors, recently purchased Saks Fifth Avenue for
about $1.5 billion. Investcorp earlier had made more than
$100 million in profit buying and selling Tiffany &amp; Co.
   "The acquisition gives F.A.O. access to KBB's capital and
international expertise," says Carol Farmer, a Boca Raton,
Fla., industry consultant who helped put the deal together.
"In return KBB has acquired a premier brand name in the
selling of toys and gifts," she says.
   When Mr. Morse and the investor group purchased F.A.O.
Schwarz in 1985, the 123-year-old company had lost much of
its glitter. With sales of only $20 million a year, and with
many of the stores in poor locations, F.A.O. Schwarz was
losing money.
   The new investors closed down some of the unprofitable
stores, moved the company's New York flagship store to a
larger location and opened a giant new store in San
Francisco. They also revitalized the company's catalog
operations and added a new line of products sold by mail. The
changes were instrumental in attracting about $7 million in
new capital from such venture capitalists as Prudential
Venture Partners, New York, and Boston's Charles River
Ventures. By the end of last year, sales at F.A.O. Schwarz
had more than doubled from 1985 and the company was highly
profitable, the company says.
   Frederick August Otto Schwarz, an immigrant from Germany,
opened the first Schwarz store in 1862, in Baltimore. After
running the company profitably for more than a century his
family sold it in 1963. The company then had a succession of
owners, including Parents Magazine Inc., W.R. Grace &amp; Co.,
and Christiana Cos., a San Diego real estate and specialty
retailer.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900801-0046
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900801-0046.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Saturday Scramble
   At Virginia S&amp;L
   Spurs a Takeover
   ---
   Thrift Regulators Shut Down
   United Savings Bank
   After Run on Deposits
   ----
   By Paulette Thomas
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
08/01/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A2
</SO>
<CO>
   USBK
</CO>
<IN>
SAVINGS AND LOANS, THRIFTS, CREDIT UNIONS (SAL)
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
</IN>
<GV>
FEDERAL GOVERNMENT (FDL)
TREASURY DEPARTMENT (TRE)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- In an unusual midweek takeover, thrift
regulators seized United Savings Bank, after the Vienna, Va.,
thrift, with $415 million in assets, experienced an
old-fashioned run on its deposits.
   Following United's report last week that it posted losses
of $11.5 million for the first six months of 1990, nervous
depositors lined up and withdrew $13 million from the thrift
on Saturday, industry sources said.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   "United was not likely to have been able to meet the
demands of its depositors or to pay its obligations in the
normal course of business," a statement from the Office of
Thrift Supervision said.
   United will operate under the management of the Resolution
Trust Corp., which will seek a buyer. All deposits at United
are insured up to $100,000, and government officials
dismissed the possibility of runs at other institutions.
   Thrift regulators waited until 4:15 p.m. yesterday to shut
the doors at United's offices.
   "Keep in mind, people around here may still relate to the
Maryland situation, where a state insurance fund ran out of
money," in the mid-1980s, a spokesman for the thrift office
said. In that case, some depositors had funds tied up for
weeks or months, while the mess was sorted out.
   In the federal thrift cleanup so far, government officials
say, depositors have received their funds in three to four
days even when an institution is liquidated. The far more
common practice is for the thrift to close over a weekend and
reopen Monday under a different name; depositors never lose
access to their funds.
   The takeover also was another signal that the
Washington-area real estate market, once considered
invulnerable to recession, is being hit by a slump,
particularly in the commercial sector. United's rapid-growth
strategy was fueled by heavy commercial real estate lending,
the thrift office said.
   The thrift office said the thrift was operating in an
unsafe and unsound condition, failed all three capital
requirements under the S&amp;L cleanup law, and relied heavily on
expensive brokered funds for its investments. United has
operated under strict federal supervision for 15 months, but
as of June 30, it classified nearly one quarter of its assets
as nonearning, troubled or losses.
   Shareholders will retain no interest in the institution
under government management. It was previously traded over
the counter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900801-0045
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900801-0045.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Dividend News:
   Telecredit Decreases
   Payout by Five Cents
   Due to Merger Pact
</HL>
<DATE>
08/01/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B6
</SO>
<CO>
   TCRD EFX
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
DIVERSIFIED FINANCIAL SERVICES, FANNIE MAE, FREDDIE MAC (FIS)
DIVIDENDS (DIV)
BUYBACKS, REDEMPTIONS, SWAP OFFERS (BBK)
</IN>
<LP>
   LOS ANGELES -- Telecredit Inc., which in June agreed to
merge with Equifax Inc., said terms of the merger pact
require it to reduce its dividend payable in September to 25
cents a share from the 30 cents paid in June.
   As reported, Los Angeles-based Telecredit, which provides
credit verification and debit-card processing services,
agreed to merge with Equifax through a stock swap valued at
about $580 million. Equifax, based in Atlanta, is a major
provider of credit reports for retailers, banks and insurers.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The new dividend is payable Sept. 7 to stock of record
Aug. 15. The cut represents an about-face from the previous
quarter's five-cent boost to 30 cents.
   Lee A. Ault III, chairman and chief executive officer,
said the company's merger agreement also calls for Telecredit
to redeem the company's so-called poison pill for five cents
per right attached to each share. The redemption is to take
place shortly before the merger, which is expected sometime
this fall. The total per-share payout over a period of time
thus would total 30 cents.
   Mr. Ault said that, should the merger not proceed,
Telecredit's board would resume payment at a rate of 30 cents
a share. Asked if there was any reason to believe that the
merger might not occur, Telecredit's executive said "nothing
is over until it's over."
   Telecredit stock yesterday fell 12.5 cents to $47.75 in
national over-the-counter trading.
   Equifax stock climbed 25 cents to $18.625 in New York
Stock Exchange composite trading.
</TEXT>
