   International Brief -- Bridgestone Corp.:
   Tire Maker's Pretax Profit
   Rose 13% in 1990 First Half
</HL>
<DATE>
08/01/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   J.BDT
</CO>
<IN>
EARNINGS (ERN)
</IN>
<LP>
   Bridgestone Corp. reported that unconsolidated pretax
profit for the six months ended June 30 rose 13%, to 46.11
billion yen ($311.6 million) from 40.82 billion yen in the
year-earlier period.
   Net income increased 27% to 24.41 billion yen, or 31.71
yen a share, from 19.21 billion yen, or 26.19 yen a share.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Sales at the Tokyo-based tire maker rose 5%, though
receipts from North American markets were flat, the company
said. Total sales were 352.21 billion yen, compared with
334.56 billion yen.
   Sales of tires rose 2% to 267.78 billion yen from 261.44
billion yen, and made up 76% of total sales. Sales in other
areas, including industrial rubber, chemicals and sports
products, increased 15% to 84.43 billion yen from 73.12
billion yen.
   Domestic sales accounted for 68% of the total and rose 6%
from a year earlier. Overseas sales rose 5%.
   Bridgestone forecast pretax profit for the full year of 97
billion yen, net income of 51 billion yen and sales of 730
billion yen.
